This guide will run you through the major steps of designing a machine leanring algorithm. We will cover:

  1. Picking a dataset
  2. Exploring and standardizing a dataset
  3. Making inital tests
  4. Deciding the features of our algorithm
  5. Implementing our algorithm
  6. Evaluating our algorithm

Picking Our Dataset

Link to download files: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jonbown/us-2020-traffic-accidents

We chose this dataset because it offers a lot of insight on US Traffic Accidents and the various factors that contribute to accidents. The dataset contains many columns detailing the different aspects of an accident such as driver age, weather conditions, and alcohol impairment that will provide a strong foundation for our analysis. With the ever growing number of drivers, we think it is crucial to understand how certain factors contribute to the severity of an accident. We also hope that our study can increase the public's awareness of common characteristics of accidents.

We've also choosen this dataset because it has recent and reliable data, and allows us to make a prediction algorithm for important issues related to traffic safety. A good dataset will be clean, consistent, and easy to understand.

Accident_XX (XX = 16, 17, 18, 19, 20) contains all the information with all the accidents throughout the years. For example, it will contain data on the casenum, total number of vehicles involved in the accident, number of pedestrians involved, date, time, alcohol involvement, and more.

Person_XX (XX = 16, 17, 18, 19, 20) contains all the information involving the people. It will have details on casenum, age, seat position, airbag, ejection, alcohol status, drug status, weight, manner of collision, and more.

Vehicle_XX (XX = 16, 17, 18, 19, 20) contains information about the vehicle. More specifically, the vehicle number in the casenum, if it had rolled over, if the vehicle was towed, if there was a fire, and more.

The different dataframes are connected by the casenum identifier.

Within the datasets, we have many different examples and variables within the 5 years of data provided. Sometimes the data has overlapped within dataframes, however it seems as though since every row has a casenum as their specific identifier it helps remove the duplicates.

Some conclusions that we can test include: Does hour in the day correlate with alcohol involvement? Is there a relationship between weather and severity. Does age impact the accident? We find with these conclusions using the different tests.

Second Correlation and Hypothesis Test:

The goal of this correlation test is to analyze the relationship between age and the number of accidents an individual or group of individuals (in the case of multi-person accidents) is involved in. We aim to determine if there is a significant correlation between a person's age and the likelihood of being involved in accidents.

Hypothesis:

H0: There is no correlation between age and the number of accidents. Age does not influence accident involvement.

HA: There is a correlation between age and the number of accidents. Age does influence accident involvement.

In[]:
data_filtered = data_2019[(data_2019['AGE'] > 0) & (data_2019['AGE'] <= 150)]

accidents_by_age = data_filtered.groupby('CASENUM').agg({
    'AGE': 'mean',
    'CASENUM': 'size'
}).rename(columns={'CASENUM': 'NUM_ACCIDENTS'})

accidents_by_age = accidents_by_age.dropna(subset=['AGE'])

corr, p_value = pearsonr(accidents_by_age['AGE'], accidents_by_age['NUM_ACCIDENTS'])
print(f'Correlation: {corr}, P-value: {p_value}')

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='AGE', y='NUM_ACCIDENTS', data=accidents_by_age)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Age vs. Number of Accidents')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Number of Accidents')
plt.show()

Correlation: -0.09845508719539112, P-value: 4.105892075953899e-115

The correlation coefficient, -0.09845508719539112, is negative and quite close to zero, indicating a very weak negative correlation between age and the number of accidents.

The p-value, 4.105892075953899e-115, is extremely small, which means the correlation is statistically significant. In other words, there is strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis that age and accident involvement are uncorrelated.

While the correlation between age and the number of accidents is statistically significant, the weak negative correlation suggests that age has very little practical influence on the likelihood of being involved in an accident. Therefore, age is not a strong predictor of accident involvement, even though there is some evidence of a slight trend toward fewer accidents as age increases. Other factors are likely to play a more substantial role in determining accident rates.

Third Correlation and Hypothesis Test:

The goal of this correlation test is to analyze the relationship between weather conditions and the severity of an accident and determine if there is a significant correlation between the two.

Hypothesis:

H0: There is no significant relationship between weather conditions and the severity of accidents.

HA: There is a significant relationship between weather conditions and the severity of accidents.

In[]:
df18_filtered = data_2018[['WEATHER', 'MAX_SEV']]

df18_filtered = df18_filtered.dropna()

contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df18_filtered['WEATHER'], df18_filtered['MAX_SEV'])

chi2, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

print(f"Chi Value: {chi2}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")


contingency_table_normalized = contingency_table.div(contingency_table.sum(1), axis=0)

contingency_table_normalized.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), cmap="viridis")

plt.title('Weather vs Accident Severity (2018)')
plt.xlabel('Weather Condition')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of Accident Severity')
plt.legend(title='Accident Severity', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Chi Value: 6153.712148220871
P-value: 0.0

The p-value is 9.40e-182 which means we reject the null hypothesis. Therefore we can conclude there is a significant relationship between weather conditions and accident severity in 2020. The large chi-square value reflects that weather conditions were an important factor in influencing the severity of accidents.

Machine Learning

In this section we will create a machine learning algorithm that helps us predict the occurence of alcohol in accidents given 8 other factors.

Now that we've viewed some of the trends present in our data, we can decide what we want to utilize for our machine learning algorithm. To reduce time complexity, we will limit our dataset to the interesting features, and can then combine each year into one dataset. We can then split our data into X, our features, and y, our targets.

9 0 2016 2 1 19 18 1 1 1

Data Interpretation:

  • PEDS: Number of pedestrians involved
  • YEAR: Year of accident
  • HOUR_IM: Hour of the day the accident took place, military time
  • AGE: Age of driver
  • SEX: Sex of driver (1:male, 2:female, 8:not reported, 9:reported as unknown)
  • WEATHER: atmospheric conditions (1:clear, 10:cloudy, 2:rain, 3:sleet/hail, 12:freezing rain/drizzle, 4:snow, 11:blowing snow, 5: fog/smog/smoke, 6:severe crosswinds, 7:blowing sand/soil/dirt, 8:other, 98:not reported, 99:reported as unknown)
  • INJ_SEV: Severity of driver injury in crash (0:none, 1:possible injury, 2:suspected minor injury, 3:suspected serious injury, 4:fatal injury, 5:injured with unknown severity, 6:died prior to crash, 9:unknown/not reported)
  • MAX_SEV: Severity of worst injury in crash (0:none, 1:possible injury, 2:suspected minor injury, 3:suspected serious injury, 4:fatal injury, 5:injured with unknown severity, 6:died prior to crash, 8:no person involved, 9:unknown/not reported)
  • ALCOHOL: Driver use of alcohol (2:no, 1:yes, 8:not reported, 9:reported as unknown)

Now we would like to show the class imbalance between "Alcohol" and "No Alcohol"

In[]:
sns.countplot(x='ALCOHOL', data=data_complete)
plt.title('Class Distribution of Alcohol Usage')
plt.xlabel('Alcohol Involvement (1 = Yes, 2 = No)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

We want to address the class imbalance in the dataset to prepare it for machine learning. Since only a small percentage of cases involve alcohol (ALCOHOL == 1), the dataset is heavily skewed towards non-alcohol cases (ALCOHOL == 2). To mitigate this, we separate the data into alcohol and non-alcohol subsets, randomly sample 500,000 rows from the majority class (non-alcohol), and combine it with all rows from the minority class (alcohol). This ensures a better balance and reduces runtime. Finally, we split the data into features (X) and target labels (y), where y represents whether alcohol was involved (binary: 1 for yes, 0 for no).

In[]:
seed = 42
np.random.seed(seed)

data_alc = data_complete[data_complete['ALCOHOL'] == 1]
data_no_alc = data_complete[data_complete['ALCOHOL'] == 2]
# only a small percentage (about 3-4%) of all the data fits the criteria of alcohol usage (43008 alcohol usage vs 893919 no alcohol usage)
# since dataset is very large (>1000000), it helps with runtime to just take a sample of it
# but to ensure that the data will have both alcohol usage and no alcohol usage, we should sample them separately

data_no_alc = data_no_alc.sample(n=500000)

data_sample = pd.concat([data_alc, data_no_alc], ignore_index=True)
data_sample

X = data_sample.drop(columns=['ALCOHOL'])
y = (data_sample['ALCOHOL'] == 1).to_numpy() # seperate by if alcohol was used as true and if it was not as false

In this section we will train and evaluate a Random Forest Classifier on our scaled training data. The Random Forest algorithm is an ensemble learning method primarily used for classification and regression tasks that builds multiple decision trees and merges their predictions to improve accuracy and control overfitting.

In[]:
# Import the necessary libraries for Random Forest Classifier and evaluation metrics
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier # For building our Random Forest model
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, accuracy_score # For our evaluation metrics
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay # For visualizing the confusion matrix

# Initialize a Random Forest Classifier
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=44)

# Train the Random Forest model using the training data
rf_model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Make predictions using the trained model on the test data
y_pred = rf_model.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Evaluate the model using accuracy, classification report, and confusion matrix
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")
print(classification_rep)

From this confusion matrix above we can see that our model is great at correctly identifying cases of No Alcohol but struggles to identify Alcohol cases. This could lead to underestimating cases of Alcohol use. The bias in the model may have to do with the significant number of No Alcohol cases vs Alcohol cases.

While Random Forests are a collection of multiple decision trees, visualizing one of the trees can provide us with some insight insights into how decisions are made in our model.

In the following code, we will extract and visualize one of the decision trees from our Random Tree Classifier.

In[]:
from sklearn.tree import plot_tree
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Train a limited-depth Random Forest
limited_tree = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, n_estimators=1, max_depth=3)
limited_tree.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Extract the decision tree from the Random Forest
tree = limited_tree.estimators_[0]

# Plot the decision tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plot_tree(
    tree,
    feature_names=X.columns,  # Feature names
    class_names=['No Alcohol', 'Alcohol'],  # Class labels
    filled=True,
    fontsize=11
)
plt.title("Decision Tree Visualization")
plt.show()

This decision tree splits data into branches based on conditions, leading to outcomes at leaf nodes. Each node contains the splitting condition, gini index (the impurity measure), sample count, class distribution, and dominant class. The root node represents the first split (in this case Injury Severity) and most samples are classified as No Alcohol which indicates this is a significant factor in determining alcohol involvement. The leaf nodes provide the final prediction (Alcohol or No Alcohol). Lower gini values indicate purer splits and the most important features are usually near the root. There was one leaf node with a gini index of 0.0 indicating perfect purity (when all samples belong to a single class, in this case Alcohol). All other leaf nodes show mixed classifications.

Overall the tree tells us that features like injury severity, age, and time related variables are important in classifying alcohol involvement in accidents.

Conclusion

In conclusion, based on all of these different tests we can provide estimates on the different scenarios and reasonings based vehicluar accidents. As stated in our introduction, we wanted to use this dataset because as drivers, we are able to relate and create predictions when it comes to accidents in vehicles. It is very important to be able to see the correlation between the accidents with alcohol and without, amongst other characteristics.

An uninformed reader would be able to understand the data as we are able to help them make their own informed opinion. We give detailed information, several graphs, and utilized machine learning to further show correlation. A user should be able to use these and see the trends within the data.

An informed reader would feel like their prior judgement is validated. However they would learn more about how accidents can also be reflected with other variables such as age and time of day.

In an ever evolving world in which we are able to drive to different states and sometimes different countries, it is important to remain safe on the roads. With this data, we know the trends that occur within accidents and can see correlations to make safer choices within our lives.
